```

Functions use:

# Stack Memory

---

# Real-World Example

Think of a stack of plates.

```text
Plate 3
Plate 2
Plate 1
```

Last plate added:

```text
Comes out first
```

LIFO.

---

# Function Calls Work Exactly Like This

Example:

```cpp
fun1()
{
    fun2();
}
```

---

### Step 1

Call:

```cpp
fun1();
```

Stack:

```text
fun1
```

---

### Step 2

fun1 calls:

```cpp
fun2();
```

Stack:

```text
fun2
fun1
```

---

### Step 3

fun2 finishes.

Removed.

Stack:

```text
fun1
```

---

### Step 4

fun1 finishes.

Stack empty.

---

# Mental Model

```text
Function Call Stack
=
To-Do Pile
```

Latest task always on top.

---

# Recursion + Call Stack

Example:

```cpp
countDown(3);
```

---

### Stack

```text
countDown(3)
```

Calls:

```text
countDown(2)
countDown(3)
```

Calls:

```text
countDown(1)
countDown(2)
countDown(3)
```

Calls:

```text
countDown(0)
countDown(1)
countDown(2)
countDown(3)
```

---

Base case reached.

Now functions return.

---

Stack becomes:

```text
countDown(1)
countDown(2)
countDown(3)
```

↓

```text
countDown(2)
countDown(3)
```

↓

```text
countDown(3)
```

↓

```text
Empty
```

---

# Why Stack Overflow Happens

Suppose:

```cpp
void fun()
{
    fun();
}
```

No base case.

Stack grows:

```text
fun
fun
fun
fun
fun
fun
...
```

Memory fills.

Crash.

---

# Interview Question 🔥

### Why is recursion memory expensive?

Because every call stores:

```text
Parameters
Local Variables
Return Address
```

inside stack memory.

---

# Recursion vs Loop

---

### Loop

```cpp
for(int i=0;i<n;i++)
```

Uses very little memory.

---

### Recursion

```cpp
fun(n)
```

Creates new stack frame each call.

Uses more memory.

---

# Mental Shortcut

Use recursion when:

```text
Problem naturally breaks into smaller versions of itself
```

Examples:

* Trees
* Backtracking
* Divide & Conquer
* DFS

